It will cost $10.99 to subscribe for a month.

post_text:
Today, we honor all those who support the Emmett School District, directly as in our wonderful staff, including our teachers, and indirectly as in everyone who produces items we use or consume. Then there are those who keep us safe and those who make sure our small community operates in a logical, efficient and forward thinking manner. Let's not forget the countless volunteers, from the school board members who spend countless hours to assist in governance, to the parents who give time in a classroom, to the civic organization members who raise money to donate to schools. Finally, there are all those parents and guardians who work so hard to help keep their children motivated for school and extracurricular activities.
Thank you! Please enjoy your day. Be safe, too.

post_text: A lot of special work went into getting ready for the first day of school at Carberry Elementary School. On Sunday, volunteers helped make these dividers for the lunchroom and some of the classrooms. Principal Greg Alexander had high praise for those who helped on Sunday. "Many thanks go out to Brendalynn Love and her family for cutting out of the mat boards and holders. Several people gathered on Sunday, August 30th, to help tape the laminate to the mats: Lara Alexander, Jeness Barr, Stefanie Joyner, Leona Bacon and her kids, Lori Eisenger, Charles and Heather West, Eric and Patti Brown and Rebekah Brune. Thanks also goes out to Jeff Ulmer for putting together the lunchroom dividers before we had lunch today so that none of the students had to eat outside or back in the classrooms." This is what makes us Emmett Proud and helps keep us safe!

post_text: We visited Carberry Elementary and Emmett High School today to check on the first day of school. Everything seemed to be pretty organized. Students seemed very excited about getting back to school. A lot of first day questions. We saw sanitizer in classrooms and at doors. A lot of masks and directional signage to keep social distancing in check, especially in hallways. Carberry Principal Mr. Alexander and his team put together some dividers for some classrooms and the lunchroom. More on that in another post. Welcome back students.

Jodie Farnsworth is with Tristan Charles and 3 others.
August 29 at 3:40 PM ·

Emmett, you are constantly amazing me with your spirit of volunteerism. I thank these uplifting young people for their contribution in making Butte View School even more exciting for our students. Dennis Deborah Fuhrmann, helped out too, but did not let me take her photo. She told me, “I didn’t do it for the notoriety, I just like to help.” We are lucky to have her and all the volunteers that have so quickly flipped Butte View back into an elementary school.

post_text:
The Emmett Board of Trustees accepted the resignation of Jody Harris Monday night and set the deadline for accepting applications to fill the vacancy.
Letters of interest, resumes and proof of residency in the Emmett School District must be submitted by 5 pm Monday, September 14, 2020. Applicants must also be a qualified voter.
Send applications to Board of Trustees Clerk Angela Mattingly at amattingly@isd221.net, or mail to Mattingly 900 S. Pine Ave, Emmett, ID 83617.
Once the applications are collected, the Board of Trustees will set a date for interviews with the applicants. It is hoped that the new trustee can be sworn in at the October 12, 2020, board meeting.
The four-year term is set to expire December 31, 2021. That means, whomever is appointed, will need to stand for election in November, 2021. To learn more about the duties of a trustee, visit https://www.emmettschools.org/domain/30.

PR2TA is excited to kick off this school year at our new location: 1805 Highway 16! Administrative staff and 6 programs will be located in this building. The programs who moved include:

Engineering (Mr. Salisbury)
Business (Mr. Wood)
Family Consumer Science (Mrs. Bromgard)
Graphic Communications (Mrs. Salisbury)
Animal Science (Mrs. Heikes)
Physical Therapy (Mrs. Shoemaker)

The remaining four programs will continue to operate on the EHS campus (Agriculture Science, Art, Culinary, and Auto).

post_text:
The Emmett School Board unanimously approved Butte View Boundary #1 to establish the new attendance zones for the reopening of Butte View Elementary this fall. Butte View will open with two classes of all-day kindergarten and two classes of first grade with the goal of eventually opening classrooms for grades through fifth grade. Before voting, Shadow Butte Principal reviewed some changes made to the two different options.
Many concerns were expressed regarding the possible split, students going to both Butte View and one of the other elementary schools for the older students. Principal Adams said the schools will work with families and schools to avoid such family splits.

Butte View will open with two classes of all-day kindergarten and two classes of first grade with the goal of eventually opening classrooms for grades through fifth grade. Before voting, Shadow Butte Principal reviewed some changes made to the two different options.
Many concerns were expressed regarding the possible split, students going to both Butte View and one of the other elementary schools for the older students. Principal Adams said the schools will work with families and schools to avoid such family splits.

Emmett High School Students please read the following information.
The school is open daily from 7 am- 3pm if you have things that you are ready to turn in you can do that at this time. This will help the process of getting your yearbook easier on May 27th and May 28th. Yearbooks will be distributed on those days from 8am- 2pm!! Yearbooks can still be purchased for $53 while supplies last. If all materials that were checked out to you are not returned, you will be billed.
Here are the things that will have to be checked off before you will get your yearbook:
* Textbooks
* Chromebooks and chargers
* Library books or fees
* clean out school and/or PE locker
* Lunch charges
* Music
Thank you for your help and cooperation through all of this!

post_text:
Goodness gracious. It's amazing how the small, but mighty county of Gem has outdone itself honoring our graduates at Emmett and Black Canyon high schools. A stranger to our small community would be amazed at all special congratulatory messages on reader boards, special signage, front windows, street banners and yard signs. Yes, it's been a difficult year for the class of 2020, but we suspect graduates will be stronger for it in the end -- we have full confidence in that. But they will also know they are being remembered and honored ... and they will remember it for the rest of their lives, no matter where they go.

Please come out in full force Saturday at 1 p.m. to wave, honor, cheer and applaud our graduating seniors. And if you haven't looked yet, please take a few moments to see the special signage and thank those businesses, parents and donors who stepped up to help cover the expenses of these special tributes. We snapped a few pictures to remind you! #Classof2020 #EmmettStrong #EmmettPride

Bus-delivered bagged lunches for the Emmett School District end May 29th. However, fewer people are picking up lunches at their designated spots as the school year comes to a close this Friday. If you don't need lunches anymore, please contact the Bus Barn at 208-365-3207, and let the team know you don't need them. It will help reduce waste.

Even though lunch deliveries end, the district will continue curb-side grab-and-go meals at the Emmett Middle School until school begins in August. Same hours, 11 am to 1 pm, Monday-Friday. This is for children 1 to 18 years of age.

post_text:
Tristin Kreiter graduates with a professional boxing contract with USA Boxing - Team USA and $4,000 in scholarships from bowling competitions. In addition to bowling and boxing, he spends free time playing football, weight lifting and naturally, boxing. He says: “Boxing is a way to get your family out the streets!”
Parent Misty Kreiter said: “The staff are beyond amazing at this school both inside and out. They really helped Tristin come out of his shell and be the man he is today.”
Tristin is going to miss his teachers, friends and playing ball at lunch.
Favorite teacher: “Dustin Kisner. He really acted like a dad I never had and he means alot to me.”

post_text: We love our teachers -- always teaching and helping. Check out this warm and fuzzy story from Jodie Farnsworth.
shared_text:
Jodie Farnsworth is with Heidee White Browne and 2 others.
May 1 at 2:11 AM ·

What do teachers do after an already full day of remote teaching and learning?

The answer is MORE, of course. After a long day of online teaching and meetings these wonderful teachers met up to collect fun May Day art projects they had asked their students to create. They had heard how hard it is for residents of nursing homes lately and they wanted to bring a little cheer into their lives through the children’s artwork. The artwork will be hung on the walls of some residents of a local nursing home. Thanks ladies for spreading hope through your actions.

Not exactly sure where the origin of "Lunch Lady Heros came from ... but this site -- with all kinds of fun activities for the kiddos -- may give you some clues: http://www.studiojjk.com/graphicnovels.html

Why bring this up today? You guessed it! We have wonderful women who go above and beyond to make sure our children are fed properly -- even during this COVID-19 pandemic! Thank you to everyone who works in our Food Services Department. And a special salute to our fearless director Tyree White!

And if you want a fun chuckle: check out this special tribute that mentions "mystery meat": http://www.studiojjk.com/lunch_lady_theme_song.mp3

This virus may change some of our traditions ... but here's the thing we know will always remain a constant. Parental pride. Look how Scott Johnson and Cindy Ponder are honoring their son, David, a 2020 Emmett High School graduate. They say pictures are worth a 1,000 words and they sure are here.
David loves sports but found his passion in Lacrosse. He is going to miss the Teachers who invested in his education and life. David plans to go college to pursue a Master's in Business and a Bachelor's in Psychology.
Congratulations David. We are all proud of you and wish you the best as you venture out to the next phase of your life. #EHSHuskies #Classof2020

Congratulations David. We are all proud of you and wish you the best as you venture out to the next phase of your life. #EHSHuskies #Classof2020

post_text: Register your future Kindergarten student today.
shared_text:
Kenneth J. Carberry Elementary School
April 20 at 2:39 PM ·

Kindergarten registration starts tomorrow, Tuesday, April 21st, for the 2020-2021 school year. We encourage parents to register their kindergarten age students, students who turn 5 years old by September 1, 2020, as soon as possible. You may pick up registration packets at either Shadow Butte or Kenneth Carberry Elementary, whichever is most convenient for you, by the front entries. Both schools will have a locked drop box located by the front entry for returning completed forms. Please return the kindergarten registration packet to the elementary school in which boundaries you CURRENTLY RESIDE, even if you are interested in full day kindergarten at Butte View. Registrations will NOT be accepted at Butte View at this time. Also, if you are able to copy your child's immunization records and proof of residency (power bill/gas bill) and attach them to your packet that would be helpful. In late spring or early summer we will make copies of birth certificates from original/official certified certificates. Kinder screening will take place at the same time.

post_text: Love this idea Musings of Emmett’s Mayor.
shared_text:
Musings of Emmett’s Mayor
April 17 at 7:10 AM ·

Mayor Gordon and Pat Petrie, after a quick train up session from City Clerk Lyleen Jerome, try their hand at tying a blue and white ribbon around the tree picked out by Public Works Director Clint Seamons. The city will soon have many such bows in place from May 1st through the 31st – along with other surprises - to honor the Class of 2020, in the hope of giving them a positive memory from what has to be one of the strangest school years in the history of Emmett’s schools, at least since the Spanish Flu.
